 21\n| goals11 = 3\n| years12 = 2013\u20132014\n| clubs12 = [[KFC Uerdingen 05]]\n| caps12 = 9\n| goals12 = 1\n| years13 = 2014\u20132017\n| clubs13 =  [[Kavala F.C.|Kavala]]\n| caps13 = 55\n| goals13 = 7\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1  = [[Greece national under-21 football team|Greece U-21]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 13\n| nationalgoals1 = 2\n| pcupdate = 14 December 2013 \n| ntupdate = 24 February 2008\n}}\n\n'''Charilaos Pappas''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: \u03a7\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03bb\u03b1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c0\u03c0\u03ac\u03c2; born 12 May 1983) is a Greek retired [[Association football|footballer]] who last played for [[Kavala F.C.|Kavala]]. A right-sided winger, Pappas was known for his speed.\n\n==Career==\nHe began his career in [[Panserraikos]], Greece. In January 2003, he moved to [[Thessaloniki]] and signed for [[Apollon Kalamarias|Apollon Kalamarias FC]]. In [[2003\u201304 in Greek football|2003\u201304]], Pappas' ten goals were a major factor in Kalamaria's winning promotion to the [[Alpha Ethniki]]. In his first season in the Greek top flight in [[2004\u201305 in Greek football|2004\u201305]], Pappas scored six times in 26 matches. Three of these goals came in away matches, where Kalamaria earned crucial points and ultimately prevailed in their battle against [[relegation]]. That season, he scored his first goal for his country in the [[2006 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship qualification|UEFA European U21 Championship qualifier]] against [[Albania]] in March 2005.\n\n[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] signed him to a five-year deal and immediately loaned him back to Kalamaria for one season. In [[2005\u201306 in Greek football|2005\u201306]], Pappas scored seven times, helping his team finish ninth in the [[Alpha Ethniki]].\n\nPappas joined Olympiacos in June. On 8 November 2006, he scored his first goal for the club in a [[Greek Cup]] match against Atsalenios FC. On 26 November 2006, he scored his first league goal for Olympiacos against [[AEL 1964|Larissa FC]]. On 27 June 2007, he signed with [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]].\n\nAfter a mediocre season, Pappas joined fellow Super League Greece team [[Skoda Xanthi FC|Skoda Xanthi]] on 6 July 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=74&n_id=4240 |title=Pappas signs for Xanthi |publisher=aekfc.gr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080708170457/http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=74 |archivedate=8 July 2008 }}</ref> On 23 June 2009, Pappas transferred to [[TSV 1860 M\u00fcnchen]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.abendzeitung-muenchen.de/inhalt.tsv-1860-loewen-holen-griechen-angreifer-pappas.5afb9825-a8ac-4115-be0a-470a17b0ba0b.html | title = L\u00f6wen holen Griechen-Angreifer Pappas | language = German | publisher = Abendzeitung | date = 23 June 2009 | accessdate = 29 October 2012}}</ref> On 31 July 2010, he signed with [[Superleague Greece|Superleague]] team [[Panetolikos]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.panaitolikos.gr/main_page/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=631:o-x-&catid=1:latest-news&Itemid=131 |title=Pappas signs for Panetolikos |publisher=panaitolikos.gr |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721082711/http://www.panaitolikos.gr/main_page/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=631%3Ao-x-&catid=1%3Alatest-news&Itemid=131 |archivedate=21 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In February 2011, he returned to [[Panserraikos]] helping his team to avoid relegation. He then moved to [[KFC Uerdingen 05]]. At the beginning of 2014\u201315 season he signed a one-year contract with [[Kavala F.C.|Kavala]].\n\n==Honours==\n;[[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n* [[Greek Super League]]: [[2006\u201307 Super League Greece|2006\u201307]]\n\n;Individual\n* [[Greek Footballer of the Year#Best player (Second Division)|Greek Second Division best player]]: 2004\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Soccerway}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box|title=[[