{"title_page": "Diocese of the Free State", "text_new": "The '''Diocese of the Free State''' is a diocese in the [[Anglican Church of Southern Africa]].\n\n==History==\nThe first service North of the [[Orange River]] to be taken by an Anglican clergyman was conducted in 1850 by \u2020[[Robert Gray (bishop of Cape Town)|Robert Gray]], the first [[Bishop of Cape Town]].  In 1863, [[Edward Twells]] was consecrated the first Bishop of the Orange Free State and the Diocese was born. This new Diocese covered the area North of the [[Orange River]], West of the [[Drakensberg]] and as far as the [[Zambezi River]] in the North.<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eagle-i.co.za/dsc_wp/wp/?page_id=12 |title=Chronological History of the Diocese of the Free State |accessdate=2014-07-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801031026/http://www.eagle-i.co.za/dsc_wp/wp/?page_id=12 |archivedate=August 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n \nThe bishop arrived in Bloemfontein on 1 October 1863, with three priests and two teachers.<ref name=\"Schoeman1991\">{{cite book|author=Karel Schoeman|title=The Wesleyan Mission in the Orange Free State, 1833 - 1854: As Described in Contemporary Accounts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqJ9QgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 September 2013|year=1991|publisher=Human & Rousseau|isbn=978-0-7981-2808-7|page=12}}</ref> [[George Mitchell (priest)|George Mitchell]] was the first priest ordained in the Diocese, in 1865.  The Cathedral was completed and consecrated in 1866.  The [[Brotherhood of St Augustine of Hippo]] was established in the diocese a year later with Canon Beckett and seven members.  Together they built  the first Anglican church in [[Thaba Nchu]], completed in 1868.  This pioneering community established the Church\u2019s work in Thaba Nchu and in places as far apart as [[Wepener]] and [[Harrismith]] and continued faithfully from their house at [[Modderpoort]] until their work was taken over by the [[Society of the Sacred Mission]] in 1902.<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\"/>\n \nThe first Diocesan Synod met in 1872 and a good foundation was laid for the organizational side of the Church\u2019s work.  Two years later the need for Sisters for nursing, teaching and visiting was recognised and the [[Community of St Michael and All Angels]] was founded in Bloemfontein.  Furthermore, the Transvaal became no longer the responsibility of Bloemfontein when the [[Anglican Diocese of Pretoria]] was formed in 1878.  Then in 1891 the scope of the diocese again changed with the formation of the [[Anglican Diocese of Mashonaland]].<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\"/>\n  \nIn 1899, the year the Anglo Boer war broke out ([[Boer Wars]]), the diocesan bishop, Wale Hicks, died. [[Allan Webb]] resigned the [[Diocese of Grahamstown|See of Grahamstown]] and came back to look after his old diocese until a new bishop could be elected.\n  \nThe first missionary conference was held in the Cathedral in 1904.  Some years later, to aid the mission work of the church and oversight, the [[Anglican Diocese of Kimberley and Kuruman]] was established in 1911.<ref name=\"LewisEdraeds1934\">\n{{cite book | title= Historical records of the Church of the Province of South Africa| last=Lewis| first=C|author2=Edwards. G.E.| date=1934| publisher=Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge| location=London|p=515}}</ref>  This was repeated again in 1950 with the formation of the [[Anglican Diocese of Lesotho]] (then, Basutoland) and in 1952, with the founding of the Anglican [[Diocese of Matabeleland]].  In 2003 the diocese changed its name to the Diocese of the Free State.<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\"/>\n\nThe seat of the diocese is in [[Bloemfontein]] in [[South Africa]].\n\n== Archdeaconries ==\nThe Free State Diocese is divided into 8 archdeaconries. The biggest archdeaconry being Goldfields. The archdeaconries are :\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Bloemfontein Archdeaconry\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Greater Bloemfontein Archdeaconry\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Sasolburg Archdeaconry\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Goldfields Archdeaconry\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Maluti Archdeaconry\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0South West Free State Archdeaconry\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Far Eastern Free State Archdeaconry\n\n-        Kroonstad Archdeaconry\n\n== Parishes ==\nThe diocese has a total of 69 parishes which are :\n\n=== Parishes : ===\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Agatha in Bultfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Luke in Hennenman\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Peter & St Paul in Hertzogville\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Michael in Hoopstad\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Holy Cross in Odendaalsrus\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mary in Odendaalsrus\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Barnabas in Theunissen\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mark in Ventersburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Alban in Virginia\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Matthew in Virginia\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Annunciation in Welkom\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Matthias in Welkom\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Peter & St Paul in Welkom\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Church of Grace in Welkom\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Clement in Winburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Paul in Arlington\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Aidan in Bethlehem\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Augustine\u2019s in Bethlehem\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Joph The Baptist in Harrismith\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Transfiguration in Harrismith\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Tsiame in Harrismith\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Matthew in Paul Roux\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0African Martyrs in Phuthaditjhaba\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Holy Cross in Reitz\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mark in Vrede\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Church of The Visitation in Warden\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Bernard The Martyr in Witzieshoek\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Andrew in Botshabelo\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Anthony in Botshabelo\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mary the Virgin in Botshabelo\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Matthew in Botshabelo\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Thomas in Botshabelo\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Augustine\u2019s in Thaba Nchu\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Lawrence in Thaba Nchu\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Cathedral of St. Andrew and St. Michaels in Bloemfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Holy Cross in Bloemfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Margaret in Bloemfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Patrick in Bloemfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Peter \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0\u00a0 in Bloemfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Philip in Bloemfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Clare in Bothaville\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St George in Kroonstad\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0The Resurrection in Kroonstad\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Joan in Viljoenskroon\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Holy Redeemer in Clocolan\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0All Saints in Ficksburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Paul in Ficksburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mark & St George in Senekal\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St James in Ladybrand\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mary & St Joseph in Ladybrand\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Columba in Marquard\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Tweespruit Anglican Church in Tweespruit\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Stephen in Hilbron\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Edwards in Parys\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mary in Parys\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Michael & All Angels in Sasolburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Peter in Sasolburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St John in Fauriesmith\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St James in Jagersfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Good Shepard in Koffiefontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Mary in Luckhoff\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Oswalds in Philippolis\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Saviors in Springfontein\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St George in Trompsburg\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Felicitas in Dewetsdorp\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Paul in Rouxville\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Peter in Smithfield\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St John in Wepener\n\n\u00b7 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0St Athanasius in Zastron\n\n==List of bishops==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color: #7F1734; color: white;\" | Bishops of Bloemfontein\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 10%;\" | From\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 10%;\" | Until\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 33%;\" | Incumbent\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 42%;\" | Notes\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1863\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1869\n| '''[[Edward Twells]]'''\n| Resigned among public allegations.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1870\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1883\n| '''[[Allan Webb]]'''\n| [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|Translated]] to [[Bishop of Grahamstown|Grahamstown]]; later [[Dean of Salisbury]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1886\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1891\n| '''[[George Knight-Bruce]]'''\n| Translated to [[Anglican Diocese of Mashonaland|Mashonaland]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1892\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1899\n| '''[[Wale Hicks]]'''\n| Died in office.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1899\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1902\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''sede vacante: [[Ranulph Vincent]], [[Dean (religion)|Dean]] of [[Bloemfontein]] was [[vicar general]].''\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1902\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1920\n| '''[[Arthur Chandler (bishop)|Arthur Chandler]]'''\n| Retired to the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1921\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1935\n| '''[[Walter Carey]]'''\n| Resigned due to ill health and returned to the United Kingdom.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1935\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1951\n| '''[[Arthur Howe-Browne]]'''\n|\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1951\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1957\n| '''[[Cecil Alderson]]'''\n| Translated from [[Anglican Diocese of Namibia|Damaraland]]; translated to [[Anglican Diocese of Mashonaland|Mashonaland]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1957\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1967\n| '''[[Bill Burnett]]'''\n| Translated to [[Bishop of Grahamstown|Grahamstown]], then [[Archbishop of Cape Town|Cape Town]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1967\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1982\n| '''[[Frederick Amoore]]'''\n|\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1982\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1997\n| '''[[Thomas Stanage]]'''\n| Previously [[Suffragan bishop]] in [[Anglican Diocese of Johannesburg|Johannesburg]] since 1978.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1997\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | ''2003''\n| '''[[Patrick Glover]]'''\n| Previously suffragan bishop in the diocese since 1994.\n\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color: #7F1734; color: white;\" | Bishops of the Free State\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | ''2003''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | ''2012''\n| '''Patrick Glover'''\n| Retired to Knysna in the Diocese of George.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | ''2013''\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | \n| '''[[Dintoe Letloenyane]]'''\n| Current\n|}\n\n==Assistant bishops==\nIn 1940, [[Stanley Haynes|S. J. Haynes]]<!--Stanley John--> was Assistant Bishop of the diocese;<ref>{{Church Times | title = Where Christians Are Not Lukewarm | archive = 1940_04_19_303 | issue = 4030 | date = 19 April 1940 | page = 303 | accessed = 27 August 2019 }}</ref> he had been in post since his October 1923 consecration as a bishop.<ref>http://www.historicalpapers.wits.ac.za/?inventoryajax/AJAX/collections&c=AB2259/R/</ref> By 1942, [[Thomas Stainton]]<!--Th. Wm STAINTON--> had been assistant bishop since 1941.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oQjSAAAAMAAJ&pg=RA1-PA399]</ref>\n\n== Coat of arms ==\nThe diocese assumed arms shortly after its inception.  They were formally granted by the [[College of Arms]] in 1951, and registered at the [[Bureau of Heraldry]] in 1992 : ''Azure,  a  saltire  Argent  surmounted of a flaming  sword erect proper; the shield ensigned of a mitre proper''.<ref name=\"Brownell2002\">{{cite book|last=Brownell|first=F. G. |authorlink=Fred Brownell|title=Heraldry in the Church of the Province of Southern Africa, 1847-2000: Coats of Arms of the Dioceses, Collegiate and Parish Churches, and the Order of Ethiopia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wYZxAAAAMAAJ|year=2002|publisher=Heraldsholme CC|isbn=978-0-620-28606-0|page=33}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|http://www.dsc.co.za/ }}\n\n{{Anglican-southern-africa}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Free State, Diocese of the}}\n[[Category:1863 establishments in the Orange Free State]]\n[[Category:Anglican Church of Southern Africa dioceses]]\n[[Category:Bishops of the Free State]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Diocese of the Free State''' is a diocese in the [[Anglican Church of Southern Africa]].\n\n==History==\nThe first service North of the [[Orange River]] to be taken by an Anglican clergyman was conducted in 1850 by \u2020[[Robert Gray (bishop of Cape Town)|Robert Gray]], the first [[Bishop of Cape Town]].  In 1863, [[Edward Twells]] was consecrated the first Bishop of the Orange Free State and the Diocese was born. This new Diocese covered the area North of the [[Orange River]], West of the [[Drakensberg]] and as far as the [[Zambezi River]] in the North.<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\">{{cite web |url=http://www.eagle-i.co.za/dsc_wp/wp/?page_id=12 |title=Chronological History of the Diocese of the Free State |accessdate=2014-07-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801031026/http://www.eagle-i.co.za/dsc_wp/wp/?page_id=12 |archivedate=August 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n \nThe bishop arrived in Bloemfontein on 1 October 1863, with three priests and two teachers.<ref name=\"Schoeman1991\">{{cite book|author=Karel Schoeman|title=The Wesleyan Mission in the Orange Free State, 1833 - 1854: As Described in Contemporary Accounts|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GqJ9QgAACAAJ|accessdate=28 September 2013|year=1991|publisher=Human & Rousseau|isbn=978-0-7981-2808-7|page=12}}</ref> [[George Mitchell (priest)|George Mitchell]] was the first priest ordained in the Diocese, in 1865.  The Cathedral was completed and consecrated in 1866.  The [[Brotherhood of St Augustine of Hippo]] was established in the diocese a year later with Canon Beckett and seven members.  Together they built  the first Anglican church in [[Thaba Nchu]], completed in 1868.  This pioneering community established the Church\u2019s work in Thaba Nchu and in places as far apart as [[Wepener]] and [[Harrismith]] and continued faithfully from their house at [[Modderpoort]] until their work was taken over by the [[Society of the Sacred Mission]] in 1902.<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\"/>\n \nThe first Diocesan Synod met in 1872 and a good foundation was laid for the organizational side of the Church\u2019s work.  Two years later the need for Sisters for nursing, teaching and visiting was recognised and the [[Community of St Michael and All Angels]] was founded in Bloemfontein.  Furthermore, the Transvaal became no longer the responsibility of Bloemfontein when the [[Anglican Diocese of Pretoria]] was formed in 1878.  Then in 1891 the scope of the diocese again changed with the formation of the [[Anglican Diocese of Mashonaland]].<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\"/>\n  \nIn 1899, the year the Anglo Boer war broke out ([[Boer Wars]]), the diocesan bishop, Wale Hicks, died. [[Allan Webb]] resigned the [[Diocese of Grahamstown|See of Grahamstown]] and came back to look after his old diocese until a new bishop could be elected.\n  \nThe first missionary conference was held in the Cathedral in 1904.  Some years later, to aid the mission work of the church and oversight, the [[Anglican Diocese of Kimberley and Kuruman]] was established in 1911.<ref name=\"LewisEdraeds1934\">\n{{cite book | title= Historical records of the Church of the Province of South Africa| last=Lewis| first=C|author2=Edwards. G.E.| date=1934| publisher=Society for Promoting Christian Knowledge| location=London|p=515}}</ref>  This was repeated again in 1950 with the formation of the [[Anglican Diocese of Lesotho]] (then, Basutoland) and in 1952, with the founding of the Anglican [[Diocese of Matabeleland]].  In 2003 the diocese changed its name to the Diocese of the Free State.<ref name=\"eagle-i.co.za\"/>\n\nThe seat of the diocese is in [[Bloemfontein]] in [[South Africa]].\n\n==List of bishops==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 95%;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color: #7F1734; color: white;\" | Bishops of Bloemfontein\n|-\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 10%;\" | From\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 10%;\" | Until\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 33%;\" | Incumbent\n! style=\"background-color: #D4B1BB; width: 42%;\" | Notes\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1863\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1869\n| '''[[Edward Twells]]'''\n| Resigned among public allegations.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1870\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1883\n| '''[[Allan Webb]]'''\n| [[Translation (ecclesiastical)|Translated]] to [[Bishop of Grahamstown|Grahamstown]]; later [[Dean of Salisbury]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1886\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1891\n| '''[[George Knight-Bruce]]'''\n| Translated to [[Anglican Diocese of Mashonaland|Mashonaland]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1892\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1899\n| '''[[Wale Hicks]]'''\n| Died in office.\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1899\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1902\n| colspan=\"2\" | ''sede vacante: [[Ranulph Vincent]], [[Dean (religion)|Dean]] of [[Bloemfontein]] was [[vicar general]].''\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: #F7F0F2;\"\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1902\n| style=\"text-align: center;\" | 1920\n| '''[[Arthur Chandler (bishop)|Arthur Chandler]]'''\n| Retired to the [[United Kingdom]].\n\n|- valign=\"top\" style=\"background-color: white;