{"title_page": "Alan Kelly (politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|Massive Bellend}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Alan Kelly\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image               = Alan Kelly (official portrait) 2020 (cropped).png\n| caption             = Kelly in 2020\n| office              = [[Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)|Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| term_start          = 3 April 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Brendan Howlin]]\n| office1             = [[Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| leader1             = [[Joan Burton]]\n| term_start1         = 4 July 2014\n| term_end1           = 20 May 2016\n| predecessor1        = Joan Burton\n| successor1          = Office not in use\n| office2             = [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]]\n| taoiseach2          = [[Enda Kenny]]\n| term_start2         = 11 July 2014\n| term_end2           = 6 May 2016\n| predecessor2        = [[Phil Hogan]]\n| successor2          = Office abolished\n| office3             = [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]]\n| taoiseach3          = Enda Kenny\n| term_start3         = 10 March 2011\n| term_end3           = 11 July 2014\n| predecessor3        = New office\n| successor3          = Office abolished\n| office4             = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start4         = [[2016 Irish general election|February 2016]]\n| term_end4           = \n| constituency4       = [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]]\n| term_start5         = [[2011 Irish general election|February 2011]]\n| term_end5           = [[2016 Irish general election|February 2016]]\n| constituency5       = [[Tipperary North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary North]]\n| office6             = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start6         = 1 July 2009\n| term_end6           = 9 March 2011\n| constituency6       = [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n| office7             = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n| term_start7         = 24 July 2007\n| term_end7           = 8 June 2009\n| constituency7       = [[Agricultural Panel]]\n| birth_name          = Alan Thomas Kelly<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Downing |url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/john-downing/new-labour-leader-howlin-has-thunder-stolen-by-rival-kelly-34734359.html |title=New Labour leader Howlin has thunder stolen by rival Kelly: Alan Kelly's 'petulant' absence from press conference raises eyebrows, writes John Downing |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |date=21 May 2016 |quote=At lunchtime yesterday, this strange process meant that Brendan Howlin was the last man standing. His colleagues - bar one Alan Thomas Kelly - accompanied him to meet the awaiting political journalists.}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1975|7|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Portroe]], [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party               = [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]\n| spouse              = Regina O'Connor {{small|(m. 2007)}}\n| children            = 2\n| education           = [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Nenagh CBS]]\n| alma_mater          = {{Unbulleted list|[[University College Cork]]|[[University College Dublin]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|alankelly.ie}}|\n}}\n'''Alan Kelly''' (born 13 July 1975) is an  Irish politician who has been the leader of the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] since April 2020. He has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]] constituency since the [[2016 Irish general election|2016 general election]].\n\nHe previously served as [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]] and [[Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)#Deputy leaders|Deputy leader of the Labour Party]] from 2014 to 2016 and [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]] from 2011 to 2014. He was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]] constituency from 2009 to 2011 and a [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]] for the [[Agricultural Panel]] from 2007 to 2009.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Alan-Kelly.S.2007-07-23/|title=Alan Kelly|work=Oireachtas Members Database|access-date=18 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKelly is from [[Portroe]] just outside [[Nenagh]], [[County Tipperary]]. He is the son of Tom and Nan Kelly. Educated at [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Nenagh CBS]], he subsequently attended [[University College Cork]] (UCC), where he completed a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in English and History in 1995. Two years later he completed a [[Master of Philosophy|M.Phil]] in Political History. Kelly continued his education at [[Boston College]], where he achieved a Certificate in Leadership in 1999. He returned to Ireland shortly after this and completed a [[Master of Business Studies|MBS]] in eCommerce in 2002. Kelly subsequently worked as an eBusiness Manager with [[Bord F\u00e1ilte]] and [[F\u00e1ilte Ireland]].\n\n==Political career==\n===Youth politics===\nKelly is thought to have been politicised from an early age. In his final year of secondary school, he canvassed for the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] during the [[1992 Irish general election|1992 general election]]. He remained active in left-wing politics in university, firstly by establishing the [[Jim Kemmy]] Branch of the Labour Party in UCC. He then became involved in a number of [[List of D\u00e1il by-elections|by-elections]], local election campaigns in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] and in the wider [[Munster]] area.\n\nKelly became [[Chairperson|Chair]] of [[Labour Youth]] in 2000, having previously served as Co-Chair. In 2001 he was a member of the General Council. In 2001 and 2002 he was director of the Tom Johnson Summer School and was also a member of the General Election Planning Committee in the period 2001-2002.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.labour.ie/alankelly/biography/|title=Alan Kelly TD - Biography|last=Party|first=The Labour|date=2015-11-05|website=The Labour Party|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n===Seanad \u00c9ireann: 2007\u20132009===\nIn 2007, Kelly launched his own political career when he secured election to [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] by the [[Agricultural Panel]]. He was the only Labour Party candidate in that grouping.<ref name=\"elecs_irl\">{{cite web |url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=8843 |title=Alan Kelly |work=ElectionsIreland.org |accessdate=2 April 2009}}</ref> After the election of [[Eamon Gilmore]] as leader of the Labour Party in 2007, Kelly was appointed as Labour Party Spokesperson on Tourism and was Seanad Spokesperson on Finance and Local Government.\n\n===European Parliament: 2009\u20132011===\nKelly was elected as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South constituency]], at the [[2009 European Parliament election in Ireland|2009 European Parliament election]], taking the last seat in a tight battle between him, [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]'s [[Toireasa Ferris]] and the [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] [[Kathy Sinnott]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Ralph |last=Riegel |url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/elections/labours-kelly-fights-off-late-sinnott-surge-1766461.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610220622/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/elections/labours-kelly-fights-off-late-sinnott-surge-1766461.html |url-status = dead|archive-date=10 June 2009 |title=Labour's Kelly fights off late Sinnott surge |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=9 June 2009}}</ref><ref name=YourMEPs>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/96667/Alan_KELLY.html |title=Alan Kelly |work=[[European Parliament]] |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Kelly was a member of the [[European Parliament]]'s [[Committee on Internal Market and Consumer Protection]].\n\n===D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann: 2011\u2013present===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Alan Kelly with Rabbitte.jpg|thumb|Kelly (left) sitting next to [[Pat Rabbitte]] at an election briefing in 2011.]] -->\nThough he promised he would see out his five-year term in the [[European Parliament]], Kelly allowed his name to go forward as a Labour Party candidate at the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]]. He ran in the [[Tipperary North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary North]] constituency and was successful, receiving 9,559 first preference votes (19.8%) and securing the third and final seat at the expense of [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]'s sitting TD, [[M\u00e1ire Hoctor]]. [[Phil Prendergast]] replaced him as MEP for the South constituency.\n\nWhen the new [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|coalition government]] was formed Kelly joined the junior ministerial ranks as [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/kenny-breaks-election-pledge-by-not-cutting-junior-ministers-147860.html |title=Kenny breaks election pledge by not cutting junior ministers |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |date=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Labour Party deputy leadership and cabinet minister (2014\u20132016)====\nIn May 2014, Kelly confirmed that he would be contesting the vote for a new deputy leader of the Labour Party following the resignation of Eamon Gilmore as party leader.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connor|first=Niall|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/three-labour-tds-have-said-they-are-interested-in-being-the-deputy-leader-of-the-party-30314463.html|title=Three Labour TDs have said they are interested in being the deputy leader of the party|date=29 May 2014|newspaper=Irish Independent}}</ref> He was elected as deputy leader of the Labour Party on 4 July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0704/628419-labour-party/ |title=Need to govern with more heart, says Joan Burton |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=4 July 2014}}</ref> On 11 July 2014, he was appointed Minister of the Environment, Community and Local Government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0711/630010-live-cabinet-reshuffle/ |title=Live: Cabinet reshuffle |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=11 July 2014}}</ref>  In January 2015, it was announced that his leader Joan Burton had nominated Kelly for the roles of Labour's director of elections and chair of Labour's national campaign committee ahead of the upcoming general election.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Fiach|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/joan-burton-appoints-alan-kelly-as-election-chief-1.2066168|title=Joan Burton appoints Alan Kelly as election chief: Labour deputy leader will chair national campaign committee for next general election|date=14 January 2015|work=[[The Irish Times]]}}</ref> \n\nHis involvement in Irish Water was extremely controversial during his tenure as minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/water/irish-water-crisis/the-sorry-history-of-irelands-water-charges-34659505.html|title=The sorry history of Ireland's water charges|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/alan-kelly-3148284-Dec2016/|title='This is an absolute joke of a D\u00e1il': Alan Kelly on sexism, his poisoned chalice and Labour's future|last=Finn|first=Christina|website=TheJournal.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Brendan Ogle of Right2Change called his comments on water 'arrogant'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/opposition-to-water-charges-off-agenda-says-alan-kelly-1.2484934|title=Opposition to water charges off agenda, says Alan Kelly|last=Holl|first=Kitty|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>, with [[Ruth Coppinger]] T.D describing some his remarks as 'delusional and unbelievably arrogant'. Paul Murphy TD described plans to take water charges from wages was a 'bullying tactic'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/|title=Minister For The Environment \u00b7 The42|website=The42|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> [[Jonathan O'Brien]] TD described him as 'arrogant Alan' in September 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cRiSzuUHlG0|title=Jonathan O'Brien TD guts 'arrogant' Housing Minister Alan Kelly for his abysmal record|last=|publisher=Sinn Fein|date=1 October 2015|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the election, Kelly remained Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government in an acting capacity during [[2016 Irish government formation|prolonged talks on government formation]]. On Sunday 24 April 2016, he represented the government at the official U.S. commemoration of the [[Centenary of the Easter Rising]] in [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==== Opposition and leadership challenges (2016\u20132020) ====\n\nShortly afterward, on Friday 13 May 2016, Kelly announced his intention to seek leadership of the Labour Party.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0513/788352-alan-kelly-labour/ Alan Kelly to run for Labour Party leadership]</ref> However, he failed to attract a nomination from his parliamentary colleagues, resulting in the unopposed appointment of [[Brendan Howlin]] as the new leader.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/brendan-howlin-chosen-to-be-new-labour-leader-1.2655555 |title=Brendan Howlin chosen to be new Labour leader |author=Sarah Bardon |work=The Irish Times |date=21 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> Grassroots efforts to put pressure on members of the parliamentary party were unsuccessful. The parliamentary party also decided not to nominate any candidates for the position of deputy leader, leaving Kelly's previous position vacant.\n\nIn September 2017, Kelly called for the [[HPV vaccine]] to be given to all schoolboys in Ireland. The vaccine's roll-out among Irish girls had recently been subject to news coverage following controversy over its alleged side effects.<ref>[http://www.thejournal.ie/labour-hpv-vaccine-3590938-Sep2017/ Labour wants the HPV vaccine to be rolled out to boys sooner rather than later<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Kelly challenged incumbent Brendan Howlin for his party's leadership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/labour-s-brendan-howlin-dismisses-alan-kelly-s-challenge-to-his-leadership-1.3613792 |title=Labour's Brendan Howlin dismisses Alan Kelly's challenge to his leadership |work=The Irish Times |date=31 August 2018 |access-date=5 September 2018}}</ref> His challenge failed due to lack of support from his parliamentary colleagues.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/alan-kelly-isolated-by-colleagues-over-labour-leadership-coup-37272243.html |title=Alan Kelly isolated by colleagues over Labour leadership coup |work=Irish Independent |date=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Kelly was re-elected to represent the [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]] constituency during the February [[2020 Irish general election|general election]], obtaining 13,222 first preference votes (9.6%) and thus securing the fourth of five available seats.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/election-2020/results/#/national/tipperary |title=Election 2020 |work=[[RT\u00c9]] |date=11 February 2020}}</ref> He was publicly backed by women's health campaigner [[Vicky Phelan]] during the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/election-2020-alan-kelly-labour-1.4168647|title=Election 2020: Alan Kelly (Labour)|last=Bowers|first=Shauna|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> As of 2020, Kelly was Labour's spokesperson on health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/labour-leadership-4-5011323-Feb2020/|title=Alan Kelly v Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in: Two TDs set to compete for Labour leadership|last=Duffy|first=R\u00f3n\u00e1n|website=TheJournal.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n==== Labour Party leader (2020\u2013present)====\n{{main|2020 Labour Party leadership election (Ireland)}}\nAfter Brendan Howlin's intention to stand down as party leader following the 2020 general election, Kelly was nominated by two of the party's six TDs; [[Se\u00e1n Sherlock]] and [[Duncan Smith (Irish politician)|Duncan Smith]]. Kelly was also publicly supported by former Labour TDs [[Jan O'Sullivan]] and [[Willie Penrose]]. Launching his [[2020 Labour Party leadership election (Ireland)|election bid]], Kelly said that a complete rebuild of the Labour Party was needed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstalk.com/news/alan-kelly-says-relish-contest-labour-leadership-969299|title=Alan Kelly says he would 'relish' a contest for Labour leadership|last=McNeice|first=Stephen|website=Newstalk|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> On 3 April 2020 he was announced as the victor in the contest and declared the new leader of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lehane |first=M\u00edche\u00e1l |date=3 April 2020 |title=Alan Kelly elected new leader of Labour Party |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2020/0403/1128197-labour-party/ |work= |location= |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKelly is married to Regina O'Connor, a [[primary school]] teacher who was raised in [[Waterville, County Kerry|Waterville]], [[County Kerry]]. The couple have two children; a daughter and a son.\n\nKelly is the author of ''A Political History of County Tipperary 1916-1997'' and has won numerous rugby and hurling medals according to his Labour Party summary.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|alankelly.ie}}\n*[http://www.alankelly.ie/ Alan Kelly's page on the Labour Party website]\n*{{MEP|96667|Alan Kelly}}\n\n{{s-start}} \n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Kathy Sinnott]]<br>{{small|[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Member of the European Parliament]] for [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]}}\n       |years  = 2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Phil Prendergast]]<br>{{small|[[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]}}}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[M\u00e1ire Hoctor]]<br>{{small|[[Fianna F\u00e1il]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]<br>for [[Tipperary North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary North]]\n       |years  = [[2011 Irish general election|2011]]\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-non|reason = New constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]]\n       |years  = 2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]]\n       |years  = 2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Office abolished}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Phil Hogan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]]\n       |years  = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Simon Coveney]]<br/><small>''as Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government''</small>}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Joan Burton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = Deputy leader of [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]\n       |years  = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Position abolished}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Ministers for the Environment of Ireland}}\n{{Members of the 23rd Seanad}}\n{{29th Government of Ireland}}\n{{Members of the European Parliament for Ireland (2009\u20132014)}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Labour Party (Ireland)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelly, Alan}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Cork]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Ireland) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Ireland) TDs]]\n[[Category:Members of the 23rd Seanad]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the Republic of Ireland 2009\u20132014]]\n[[Category:Ministers for the Environment (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Ireland) senators]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Labour Party (Ireland)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Alan Kelly\n| honorific-suffix    = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image               = Alan Kelly (official portrait) 2020 (cropped).png\n| caption             = Kelly in 2020\n| office              = [[Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)|Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| term_start          = 3 April 2020\n| term_end            = \n| predecessor         = [[Brendan Howlin]]\n| office1             = [[Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)#Deputy leaders|Deputy Leader of the Labour Party]]\n| leader1             = [[Joan Burton]]\n| term_start1         = 4 July 2014\n| term_end1           = 20 May 2016\n| predecessor1        = Joan Burton\n| successor1          = Office not in use\n| office2             = [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]]\n| taoiseach2          = [[Enda Kenny]]\n| term_start2         = 11 July 2014\n| term_end2           = 6 May 2016\n| predecessor2        = [[Phil Hogan]]\n| successor2          = Office abolished\n| office3             = [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]]\n| taoiseach3          = Enda Kenny\n| term_start3         = 10 March 2011\n| term_end3           = 11 July 2014\n| predecessor3        = New office\n| successor3          = Office abolished\n| office4             = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start4         = [[2016 Irish general election|February 2016]]\n| term_end4           = \n| constituency4       = [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]]\n| term_start5         = [[2011 Irish general election|February 2011]]\n| term_end5           = [[2016 Irish general election|February 2016]]\n| constituency5       = [[Tipperary North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary North]]\n| office6             = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start6         = 1 July 2009\n| term_end6           = 9 March 2011\n| constituency6       = [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]\n| office7             = [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]]\n| term_start7         = 24 July 2007\n| term_end7           = 8 June 2009\n| constituency7       = [[Agricultural Panel]]\n| birth_name          = Alan Thomas Kelly<ref>{{cite news |first=John |last=Downing |url=http://www.independent.ie/opinion/columnists/john-downing/new-labour-leader-howlin-has-thunder-stolen-by-rival-kelly-34734359.html |title=New Labour leader Howlin has thunder stolen by rival Kelly: Alan Kelly's 'petulant' absence from press conference raises eyebrows, writes John Downing |newspaper=[[Irish Independent]] |date=21 May 2016 |quote=At lunchtime yesterday, this strange process meant that Brendan Howlin was the last man standing. His colleagues - bar one Alan Thomas Kelly - accompanied him to meet the awaiting political journalists.}}</ref>\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1975|7|13|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Portroe]], [[County Tipperary]], Ireland\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party               = [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]\n| spouse              = Regina O'Connor {{small|(m. 2007)}}\n| children            = 2\n| education           = [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Nenagh CBS]]\n| alma_mater          = {{Unbulleted list|[[University College Cork]]|[[University College Dublin]]}}\n| website             = {{URL|alankelly.ie}}|\n}}\n'''Alan Kelly''' (born 13 July 1975) is an  Irish politician who has been the leader of the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] since April 2020. He has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]] constituency since the [[2016 Irish general election|2016 general election]].\n\nHe previously served as [[Minister for Housing, Planning and Local Government|Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]] and [[Leader of the Labour Party (Ireland)#Deputy leaders|Deputy leader of the Labour Party]] from 2014 to 2016 and [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]] from 2011 to 2014. He was a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]] constituency from 2009 to 2011 and a [[Seanad \u00c9ireann|Senator]] for the [[Agricultural Panel]] from 2007 to 2009.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web|url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Alan-Kelly.S.2007-07-23/|title=Alan Kelly|work=Oireachtas Members Database|access-date=18 February 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nKelly is from [[Portroe]] just outside [[Nenagh]], [[County Tipperary]]. He is the son of Tom and Nan Kelly. Educated at [[Congregation of Christian Brothers|Nenagh CBS]], he subsequently attended [[University College Cork]] (UCC), where he completed a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in English and History in 1995. Two years later he completed a [[Master of Philosophy|M.Phil]] in Political History. Kelly continued his education at [[Boston College]], where he achieved a Certificate in Leadership in 1999. He returned to Ireland shortly after this and completed a [[Master of Business Studies|MBS]] in eCommerce in 2002. Kelly subsequently worked as an eBusiness Manager with [[Bord F\u00e1ilte]] and [[F\u00e1ilte Ireland]].\n\n==Political career==\n===Youth politics===\nKelly is thought to have been politicised from an early age. In his final year of secondary school, he canvassed for the [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] during the [[1992 Irish general election|1992 general election]]. He remained active in left-wing politics in university, firstly by establishing the [[Jim Kemmy]] Branch of the Labour Party in UCC. He then became involved in a number of [[List of D\u00e1il by-elections|by-elections]], local election campaigns in [[Cork (city)|Cork]] and in the wider [[Munster]] area.\n\nKelly became [[Chairperson|Chair]] of [[Labour Youth]] in 2000, having previously served as Co-Chair. In 2001 he was a member of the General Council. In 2001 and 2002 he was director of the Tom Johnson Summer School and was also a member of the General Election Planning Committee in the period 2001-2002.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.labour.ie/alankelly/biography/|title=Alan Kelly TD - Biography|last=Party|first=The Labour|date=2015-11-05|website=The Labour Party|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>\n\n===Seanad \u00c9ireann: 2007\u20132009===\nIn 2007, Kelly launched his own political career when he secured election to [[Seanad \u00c9ireann]] by the [[Agricultural Panel]]. He was the only Labour Party candidate in that grouping.<ref name=\"elecs_irl\">{{cite web |url=http://electionsireland.org/candidate.cfm?ID=8843 |title=Alan Kelly |work=ElectionsIreland.org |accessdate=2 April 2009}}</ref> After the election of [[Eamon Gilmore]] as leader of the Labour Party in 2007, Kelly was appointed as Labour Party Spokesperson on Tourism and was Seanad Spokesperson on Finance and Local Government.\n\n===European Parliament: 2009\u20132011===\nKelly was elected as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] for the [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South constituency]], at the [[2009 European Parliament election in Ireland|2009 European Parliament election]], taking the last seat in a tight battle between him, [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]'s [[Toireasa Ferris]] and the [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] [[Kathy Sinnott]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Ralph |last=Riegel |url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/elections/labours-kelly-fights-off-late-sinnott-surge-1766461.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610220622/http://www.independent.ie/national-news/elections/labours-kelly-fights-off-late-sinnott-surge-1766461.html |url-status = dead|archive-date=10 June 2009 |title=Labour's Kelly fights off late Sinnott surge |newspaper=Irish Independent |date=9 June 2009}}</ref><ref name=YourMEPs>{{cite web |url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/96667/Alan_KELLY.html |title=Alan Kelly |work=[[European Parliament]] |accessdate=26 January 2012}}</ref> Kelly was a member of the [[European Parliament]]'s [[Committee on Internal Market and Consumer Protection]].\n\n===D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann: 2011\u2013present===\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Alan Kelly with Rabbitte.jpg|thumb|Kelly (left) sitting next to [[Pat Rabbitte]] at an election briefing in 2011.]] -->\nThough he promised he would see out his five-year term in the [[European Parliament]], Kelly allowed his name to go forward as a Labour Party candidate at the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]]. He ran in the [[Tipperary North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary North]] constituency and was successful, receiving 9,559 first preference votes (19.8%) and securing the third and final seat at the expense of [[Fianna F\u00e1il]]'s sitting TD, [[M\u00e1ire Hoctor]]. [[Phil Prendergast]] replaced him as MEP for the South constituency.\n\nWhen the new [[Government of the 31st D\u00e1il|coalition government]] was formed Kelly joined the junior ministerial ranks as [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/kenny-breaks-election-pledge-by-not-cutting-junior-ministers-147860.html |title=Kenny breaks election pledge by not cutting junior ministers |work=[[Irish Examiner]] |date=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Labour Party deputy leadership and cabinet minister (2014\u20132016)====\nIn May 2014, Kelly confirmed that he would be contesting the vote for a new deputy leader of the Labour Party following the resignation of Eamon Gilmore as party leader.<ref>{{cite news|last=O'Connor|first=Niall|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/three-labour-tds-have-said-they-are-interested-in-being-the-deputy-leader-of-the-party-30314463.html|title=Three Labour TDs have said they are interested in being the deputy leader of the party|date=29 May 2014|newspaper=Irish Independent}}</ref> He was elected as deputy leader of the Labour Party on 4 July 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0704/628419-labour-party/ |title=Need to govern with more heart, says Joan Burton |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=4 July 2014}}</ref> On 11 July 2014, he was appointed Minister of the Environment, Community and Local Government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0711/630010-live-cabinet-reshuffle/ |title=Live: Cabinet reshuffle |work=RT\u00c9 News |date=11 July 2014}}</ref>  In January 2015, it was announced that his leader Joan Burton had nominated Kelly for the roles of Labour's director of elections and chair of Labour's national campaign committee ahead of the upcoming general election.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kelly|first=Fiach|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/joan-burton-appoints-alan-kelly-as-election-chief-1.2066168|title=Joan Burton appoints Alan Kelly as election chief: Labour deputy leader will chair national campaign committee for next general election|date=14 January 2015|work=[[The Irish Times]]}}</ref> \n\nHis involvement in Irish Water was extremely controversial during his tenure as minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/water/irish-water-crisis/the-sorry-history-of-irelands-water-charges-34659505.html|title=The sorry history of Ireland's water charges|website=independent|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/alan-kelly-3148284-Dec2016/|title='This is an absolute joke of a D\u00e1il': Alan Kelly on sexism, his poisoned chalice and Labour's future|last=Finn|first=Christina|website=TheJournal.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> Brendan Ogle of Right2Change called his comments on water 'arrogant'<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/opposition-to-water-charges-off-agenda-says-alan-kelly-1.2484934|title=Opposition to water charges off agenda, says Alan Kelly|last=Holl|first=Kitty|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref>, with [[Ruth Coppinger]] T.D describing some his remarks as 'delusional and unbelievably arrogant'. Paul Murphy TD described plans to take water charges from wages was a 'bullying tactic'.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/|title=Minister For The Environment \u00b7 The42|website=The42|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> [[Jonathan O'Brien]] TD described him as 'arrogant Alan' in September 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cRiSzuUHlG0|title=Jonathan O'Brien TD guts 'arrogant' Housing Minister Alan Kelly for his abysmal record|last=|publisher=Sinn Fein|date=1 October 2015|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the election, Kelly remained Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government in an acting capacity during [[2016 Irish government formation|prolonged talks on government formation]]. On Sunday 24 April 2016, he represented the government at the official U.S. commemoration of the [[Centenary of the Easter Rising]] in [[Manhattan]], [[New York (state)|New York]].\n\n==== Opposition and leadership challenges (2016\u20132020) ====\n\nShortly afterward, on Friday 13 May 2016, Kelly announced his intention to seek leadership of the Labour Party.<ref>[http://www.rte.ie/news/2016/0513/788352-alan-kelly-labour/ Alan Kelly to run for Labour Party leadership]</ref> However, he failed to attract a nomination from his parliamentary colleagues, resulting in the unopposed appointment of [[Brendan Howlin]] as the new leader.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/brendan-howlin-chosen-to-be-new-labour-leader-1.2655555 |title=Brendan Howlin chosen to be new Labour leader |author=Sarah Bardon |work=The Irish Times |date=21 May 2016 |accessdate=21 May 2016}}</ref> Grassroots efforts to put pressure on members of the parliamentary party were unsuccessful. The parliamentary party also decided not to nominate any candidates for the position of deputy leader, leaving Kelly's previous position vacant.\n\nIn September 2017, Kelly called for the [[HPV vaccine]] to be given to all schoolboys in Ireland. The vaccine's roll-out among Irish girls had recently been subject to news coverage following controversy over its alleged side effects.<ref>[http://www.thejournal.ie/labour-hpv-vaccine-3590938-Sep2017/ Labour wants the HPV vaccine to be rolled out to boys sooner rather than later<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Kelly challenged incumbent Brendan Howlin for his party's leadership.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/labour-s-brendan-howlin-dismisses-alan-kelly-s-challenge-to-his-leadership-1.3613792 |title=Labour's Brendan Howlin dismisses Alan Kelly's challenge to his leadership |work=The Irish Times |date=31 August 2018 |access-date=5 September 2018}}</ref> His challenge failed due to lack of support from his parliamentary colleagues.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/alan-kelly-isolated-by-colleagues-over-labour-leadership-coup-37272243.html |title=Alan Kelly isolated by colleagues over Labour leadership coup |work=Irish Independent |date=1 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, Kelly was re-elected to represent the [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]] constituency during the February [[2020 Irish general election|general election]], obtaining 13,222 first preference votes (9.6%) and thus securing the fourth of five available seats.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/election-2020/results/#/national/tipperary |title=Election 2020 |work=[[RT\u00c9]] |date=11 February 2020}}</ref> He was publicly backed by women's health campaigner [[Vicky Phelan]] during the election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/election-2020-alan-kelly-labour-1.4168647|title=Election 2020: Alan Kelly (Labour)|last=Bowers|first=Shauna|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2020-02-15}}</ref> As of 2020, Kelly was Labour's spokesperson on health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thejournal.ie/labour-leadership-4-5011323-Feb2020/|title=Alan Kelly v Aodh\u00e1n \u00d3 R\u00edord\u00e1in: Two TDs set to compete for Labour leadership|last=Duffy|first=R\u00f3n\u00e1n|website=TheJournal.ie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-17}}</ref>\n\n==== Labour Party leader (2020\u2013present)====\n{{main|2020 Labour Party leadership election (Ireland)}}\nAfter Brendan Howlin's intention to stand down as party leader following the 2020 general election, Kelly was nominated by two of the party's six TDs; [[Se\u00e1n Sherlock]] and [[Duncan Smith (Irish politician)|Duncan Smith]]. Kelly was also publicly supported by former Labour TDs [[Jan O'Sullivan]] and [[Willie Penrose]]. Launching his [[2020 Labour Party leadership election (Ireland)|election bid]], Kelly said that a complete rebuild of the Labour Party was needed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstalk.com/news/alan-kelly-says-relish-contest-labour-leadership-969299|title=Alan Kelly says he would 'relish' a contest for Labour leadership|last=McNeice|first=Stephen|website=Newstalk|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref> On 3 April 2020 he was announced as the victor in the contest and declared the new leader of the Labour Party.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lehane |first=M\u00edche\u00e1l |date=3 April 2020 |title=Alan Kelly elected new leader of Labour Party |url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2020/0403/1128197-labour-party/ |work= |location= |access-date=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nKelly is married to Regina O'Connor, a [[primary school]] teacher who was raised in [[Waterville, County Kerry|Waterville]], [[County Kerry]]. The couple have two children; a daughter and a son.\n\nKelly is the author of ''A Political History of County Tipperary 1916-1997'' and has won numerous rugby and hurling medals according to his Labour Party summary.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|alankelly.ie}}\n*[http://www.alankelly.ie/ Alan Kelly's page on the Labour Party website]\n*{{MEP|96667|Alan Kelly}}\n\n{{s-start}} \n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Kathy Sinnott]]<br>{{small|[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = {{nowrap|[[Member of the European Parliament]] for [[South (European Parliament constituency)|South]]}}\n       |years  = 2009\u20132011}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Phil Prendergast]]<br>{{small|[[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]}}}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[M\u00e1ire Hoctor]]<br>{{small|[[Fianna F\u00e1il]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]<br>for [[Tipperary North (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary North]]\n       |years  = [[2011 Irish general election|2011]]\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Constituency abolished}}\n{{s-non|reason = New constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] for [[Tipperary (D\u00e1il constituency)|Tipperary]]\n       |years  = 2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il|Minister of State for Public and Commuter Transport]]\n       |years  = 2011\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Office abolished}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Phil Hogan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Minister for the Environment, Community and Local Government]]\n       |years  = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Simon Coveney]]<br/><small>''as Minister for Housing, Planning, Community and Local Government''</small>}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Joan Burton]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = Deputy leader of [[Labour Party (Ireland)|Labour Party]]\n       |years  = 2014\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after  = Position abolished}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Ministers for the Environment of Ireland}}\n{{Members of the 23rd Seanad}}\n{{29th Government of Ireland}}\n{{Members of the European Parliament for Ireland (2009\u20132014)}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Labour Party (Ireland)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kelly, Alan}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Cork]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Ireland) MEPs]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Ireland) TDs]]\n[[Category:Members of the 23rd Seanad]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the Republic of Ireland 2009\u20132014]]\n[[Category:Ministers for the Environment (Ireland)]]\n[[Category:Ministers of State of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Tipperary]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (Ireland) senators]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Labour Party (Ireland)]]\n", "name_user": "81.98.142.8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Accurate Description)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Kelly_(politician)"}
{"title_page": "K. H. D. Haley", "text_new": "'''Kenneth Harold Dobson Haley''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (19 April 1920 &ndash; 2 July 1997) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] historian who specialised in seventeenth century British and [[Netherlands|Dutch]] history.<ref name=\"Independent\">Clyde Binfield, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-professor-kenneth-haley-1244977.html Obituary: Professor Kenneth Haley]', ''The Independent'' (11 August 1997), retrieved 9 July 2018.</ref>\n\nHaley was born in [[Southport]], [[Merseyside]]. He attended Huddersfield College before winning a scholarship to [[Balliol College, Oxford]], where he gained a First in history.<ref name=\"Independent\"/> He taught at the [[University of Sheffield]]'s history department from 1947 to 1982, spending the last 20 years as Professor of Modern History.<ref name=\"Independent\"/> In 1968 the [[Oxford University Press]] published his ''[[magnum opus]]'', a biography of the leader of the first [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]], [[Anthony Ashley Cooper, 1st Earl of Shaftesbury]].<ref name=\"Independent\"/> He was awarded a Fellowship of the [[British Academy]] in 1987.<ref name=\"Independent\"/>\n\nHe was a [[Methodism|Methodist]] and in 1948 he married Iris Houghton.<ref name=\"Independent\"/>\n\n==Works==\n*''William of Orange and the English Opposition 1672-1674'' (1953).\n*''The First Earl of Shaftesbury'' (1968).\n*''The British and the Dutch: Political and Cultural Relations Through the Ages'' (1968).\n*''The Dutch in the Seventeenth Century'' (1972).\n*''An English Diplomat in the Low Countries: Sir William Temple and John De Witt 1655-1672'' (1986).\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Bob Moore, 'Ken Haley: An Appreciation', in Hugh Dunthorne and Michael Wintle (eds.), ''The Historical Imagination in Nineteenth-Century Britain and the Low Countries'' (Leiden: Brill, 2013), pp. xvii-xxi.\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haley, Kenneth}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Dutch Republic]]\n[[Category:20th-century British historians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English Methodists]]\n[[Category:People from Southport]]\n", "text_old": "'''Kenneth Harold Dobson Haley''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FBA}} (19 April 1920 &ndash; 2 July 1997) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] historian who specialised in seventeenth century British and [[Netherlands|Dutch]] history.<ref name=\"Independent\">Clyde Binfield, '[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/obituary-professor-kenneth-haley-1244977.html Obituary: Professor Kenneth Haley]', ''The Independent'' (11 August 1997), retrieved 9 July 2018.</ref>\n\nHaley was born in [[Southport]], [[Merseyside]]. He attended Huddersfield College before winning a scholarship to [[Balliol College, Oxford]], where he gained a First in history.<ref name=\"Independent\"/> He taught at the [[University of Sheffield]]'s history department from 1947 to 1982, spending the last 20 years as Professor of Modern History.<ref name=\"Independent\"/> In 1968 the [[Oxford University Press]] published his ''[[magnum opus]]'', a biography of the leader of the first [[Whigs (British political party)|Whigs]], [[Anthony Ashley Cooper, 1st Earl of Shaftesbury]].<ref name=\"Independent\"/> He was awarded a Fellowship of the [[British Academy]] in 1987.<ref name=\"Independent\"/> \n\nHe was a [[Methodism|Methodist]] and in 1948 he married Iris Houghton.<ref name=\"Independent\"/> \n\n==Works==\n*''William of Orange and the English Opposition 1672-1674'' (1953).\n*''The First Earl of Shaftesbury'' (1968).\n*''The British and the Dutch: Political and Cultural Relations Through the Ages'' (1968).\n*''The Dutch in the Seventeenth Century'' (1972).\n*''An English Diplomat in the Low Countries: Sir William Temple and John De Witt 1655-1672'' (1986).\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Bob Moore, 'Ken Haley: An Appreciation', in Hugh Dunthorne and Michael Wintle (eds.), ''The Historical Imagination in Nineteenth-Century Britain and the Low Countries'' (Leiden: Brill, 2013), pp. xvii-xxi.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haley, Kenneth}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Dutch Republic]]\n[[Category:20th-century British historians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:English Methodists]]\n[[Category:People from Southport]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K._H._D._Haley"}
{"title_page": "Three Days to Vegas", "text_new": "'''''Three Days to Vegas''''' is a 2007 American [[comedy film]] directed by Charlie Picerni and starring [[Peter Falk]], [[Rip Torn]], [[George Segal]],  and [[Bill Cobbs]]. The story follows four elderly male retirees who take a road trip to [[Las Vegas]] to stop the impending marriage of one of their daughters, played by [[Nancy Young]]. Cobbs replaced iconic actor [[Ossie Davis]] in the cast after Davis died during production.<ref>{{cite news|title=Veteran actor takes over for Ossie Davis on 'Retirement'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/feb/12/entertainment/et-ossie12|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=12 February 2005}}</ref> The film features various prominent actors in supporting roles, including [[Billy Burke (actor)|Billy Burke]], [[Chris Diamantopoulos]], [[Reginald VelJohnson]], and [[Taylor Negron]].\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Peter Falk]]... Gus 'Fitzy' Fitzgerald\n*[[Rip Torn]]... Joe Wallace\n*[[George Segal]]... Dominic Spinuzzi\n*[[Bill Cobbs]]... Marvin Jeffries\n*[[Billy Burke (actor)|Billy Burke]]...Billy\n*[[Nancy Young]]...Elizabeth Fitzgerald\n*[[Chris Diamantopoulos]]... Laurent Perrier\n*[[Taylor Negron]]... Antoine\n*[[Coolio]]... The Flow\n*[[Charlie Murphy]]... Andre\n*[[Reginald VelJohnson]]... RJ Jackson\n*[[Xavier Lamar Truesdell|Xavier Truesdell]]... Flo's Entourage\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0438365|Three Days to Vegas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Three Days to Vegas}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-comedy-film-stub}}\n[[Category:2000s comedy films]]\n", "text_old": "'''''Three Days to Vegas''''' is a 2007 American comedy film, directed by Charlie Picerni and starring [[Peter Falk]], [[Rip Torn]], [[George Segal]],  and [[Bill Cobbs]]. The story follows four elderly male retirees who take a road trip to [[Las Vegas]] to stop the impending marriage of one of their daughters, played by [[Nancy Young]]. Cobbs replaced iconic actor [[Ossie Davis]] in the cast after Davis died during production.<ref>{{cite news|title=Veteran actor takes over for Ossie Davis on 'Retirement'|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2005/feb/12/entertainment/et-ossie12|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=12 February 2005}}</ref> The film features various prominent actors in supporting roles, including [[Billy Burke (actor)|Billy Burke]], [[Chris Diamantopoulos]], [[Reginald VelJohnson]], and [[Taylor Negron]].\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Peter Falk]]... Gus 'Fitzy' Fitzgerald\n*[[Rip Torn]]... Joe Wallace\n*[[George Segal]]... Dominic Spinuzzi\n*[[Bill Cobbs]]... Marvin Jeffries\n*[[Billy Burke (actor)|Billy Burke]]...Billy\n*[[Nancy Young]]...Elizabeth Fitzgerald\n*[[Chris Diamantopoulos]]... Laurent Perrier\n*[[Taylor Negron]]... Antoine\n*[[Coolio]]... The Flow\n*[[Charlie Murphy]]... Andre\n*[[Reginald VelJohnson]]... RJ Jackson\n*[[Xavier Lamar Truesdell|Xavier Truesdell]]... Flo's Entourage\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0438365|Three Days to Vegas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Three Days to Vegas}}\n[[Category:2007 films]]\n[[Category:American comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Films shot in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n\n\n{{2000s-comedy-film-stub}}\n[[Category:2000s comedy films]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_Days_to_Vegas"}
